    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The issue is that your two Integer objects are just that, objects. They do not match because you are comparing your two object references, not the values within. Obviously <code>.equals</code> is overridden to provide a value comparison as opposed to an object reference comparison.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 59511,
      "reputation" : 36108,
      "user_id" : 178060,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 92,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e61aa9f3d632781569b0115b9f3154fd?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "wheaties",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/178060/wheaties"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1283533628,
    "creation_date" : 1283533628,
    "answer_id" : 3637959,
    "question_id" : 3637936,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p><code>Integer</code> refers to the reference, that is, when comparing references you're comparing if they point to the same object, not value.  Hence, the issue you're seeing.  The reason it works so well with plain <code>int</code> types is that it unboxes the value contained by the <code>Integer</code>.</p>\n\n<p>May I add that if you're doing what you're doing, why have the <code>if</code> statement to begin with?</p>\n\n<pre><code>mismatch = ( cdiCt != null &amp;&amp; cdsCt != null &amp;&amp; !cdiCt.equals( cdsCt ) );\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
