        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/k9b4h.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Terran",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3409441/terran"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1600679025,
      "post_id" : 61241480,
      "comment_id" : 113152368,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "That&#39;s because <code>==</code> more or less compares values on the stack. So for primitives it&#39;s their values and for objects it&#39;s their references (hashcode). <code>.equals</code> compares whatever was defined in the overriden method of the corresponding class. Note that if there&#39;s no override, the default <code>.equals</code> in <code>Object</code> does the following: <code>return (this == obj);</code>."
    } ],
